<Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
I am VERY pleased with this new local brewery. We have gone in four times now, so I waited to make sure the excellent experience was highly repeatable. It is. The beer is fresh and delicious, the owners and servers are friendly, and the food is excellent. Food has actually improved. The food was good at first, but we went yesterday and had the Banh mi and the Hot chicken sandwich and both were truly excellent. The only thing that would make this brewery perfect is if they had dark beers, including an imperial stout. I know it's summer and I hope they'll have these in the cool weather, but pretty please can you have an imperial stout year round?? Thanks Humdinger for bringing great beer to the village,  we are now loyal customers.< /Text>

<Text>Crissy Field is part of an urban national park, which, due to its location and scenic views, is popular with both locals, tourists, and dogs.

Crissy Field reopened in 2001. New and rebuilt sidewalks, boardwalks, and trails connect the field north to Fort Point, the Warming Hut (a cafe), and south to the Crissy Field Center, an environmental education center, and the Marina District. Since that time many buildings were restored and leased out as housing, office space, retail, and recreational facilities. The old temporary wood barracks were demolished and the grass airfield restored. Letterman Army Hospital, a large concrete structure, literally was ground to dust and the concrete recycled. In its place George Lucas relocated Industrial Light & Magic.< /Text>< pics>

<Text>Dr. Silvera came highly recommended to me by several different family friends when I first moved to Los Angeles and was very reticent about looking for a new dentist after a bad experience with one in New York. I had been looking for someone knowledgeable about TMJ because mine was particularly painful and at the time (this was 5-6 years ago), Dr. Silvera had a really great and effective physical therapy program for TMJ that I did for about a year until I didn't need it. I've been going to him ever since.

Dr. Silvera always gives you all the time you need. He's scheduled longer visits for me because of my TMJ. When he heard through the grapevine that I had been taken to the hospital for an emergency, he came to the hospital personally to say hello. I can say without a doubt that I trust him implicitly.

The staff is always friendly. Marsha and the dental assistants always ask after my family.  I appreciate the texts and call reminders for appointments as my calendar app is not as trustworthy as these folks. I don't have dental insurance and I find everything to be very affordable.</Text>< rating>

< Text>
I've been coming here for several years but my appointment last night compelled me want to write a review. I arrived at 6:15pm asking to do a chest x-ray but the front desk mentioned that the technician was on his way out for the night. They went to go check to see if he could still see me, which he happily did. The technician was an absolute delight and said "You know why I stayed? Because patients come first." An angel!! I never feel nervous or shamed for coming in here and I always know I will be taken care of.</Text>

< Text>
I was given a very strong recommendation to go here for an emergency by my pharmacist. Get here before 7.20, and remember how bad LA traffic is. I was late, and ready to give my first born child to squeeze in. Fortunately no such item was on the invoice. I'm so thankful for the staff for fitting me in. Don't ask this of them though, they do good work and deserve their rest.

I was a trainwreck, my psychiatrist dropped me without warning after days in withdrawal waiting for an appointment. Those days were the difference between feeling like a functioning major start-up founder and a a homeless crack addict. We don't go to urgent care on our best days, tey tend to be our worst, and it can make us feel small. I am so used to doctors not treating me with respect or dignity that I sat waiting, in tears (see UCLA Urgent Care review). Dr J Sudarski, a kind intelligent, beautiful lady with grey hair that spoke to her disinterest in LA's typically superficiality, promptly saw me, understanding before I had a chance to throw out all my self respect. I stuttered..in shock..not understanding why I was being treated without bias or judgement. She gently ignored my question, as if it were insane to ask.

It was insane, but that is literally the difference in care between two clinics a mile apart. Bookmark this place, even if you don't need it today, because you might not have time to comb reviews when you have the worst day of your life, and you need it to get better.< /Text>

< review>
This center is one of the reasons all Americans have out of control insurance premiums.  I have excellent insurance, but out of genuine interest enquired about the cost of my care ( for a broken pinkie toe) every step of the way.  I was told that it was $150 to see a doctor. OK.  Because I have excellent insurance, the upselling started immediately.  I was offered a pain shot before I was examined. I was in no pain and the shot I was offered was essentially liquid tylenol. (30 cents worth, but who knows what they bill that at) That doctor recommended an x ray and before I consented, I made sure that I asked how much that would cost too. The doctor said, "I can't know that", so I waited to talk to the billing department and was told a foot x ray was $45.   By my calculations,  the cost of my care was $195.  The doctor also tried to sell me a "boot" to protect my toe and further painkillers from their in house pharmacy. ( Convenient but check your coverage) Imagine my surprise six weeks later, to see that my insurance company was billed $900 for my visit- 5 minutes with a doctor plus a foot x ray. The x ray was billed to insurance at $100. Cigna paid the "negotiated discount rate"of $405.09. That is DOUBLE the retail rate of the services rendered. I spoke to several staff members at SM Urgent Care, and was told that an uninsured patient would have been charged $235 for the visit.  This overcharging of insurance companies  is beyond unethical, although in my communications with the billing staff, I was assured it was legal.

It is why all of American premiums are so ridiculous. It is absolutely disgusting. No wonder we are where we are  with national healthcare when a simple foot x ray is billed at $900.   If you have good insurance, Santa Monica Urgent Care will try to cash in on you. Please fight back and continue to ask questions and post your experiences.  If you'd like to learn more, read An American Sickness by Elisabeth Rosenthal.  We should all fight back against rip offs like this one.  FYI The medical care was adequate.</review>

< Review>
The staff was friendly enough and the Doctor was fine where this place got low marks is there speed. We got here and the place was empty of patients and we were told we were lucky. We filled out the normal questionnaire and was showed to a room immediately and told the doctor would be right in, 45 minutes later I asked how much longer and they told me he now has our questionnaire and will be in in 5 minutes, 20 minutes later he finally came in. The Doctor did the quick checkup we came in for and took us out where the front desk said we had to wait for them to get the chart from the Doctor for some reason and seemed to imply we needed something further. We waited a half hour and I finally got up to ask what were waiting for. She said "let me check on your chart" came back a second later and said "actually you're all taken care of by the insurance and your paperwork has been faxed over to your other doctor" so we were waiting for nothing. We came in being first and no other patients there and 2 and a half hours later we left for literally a check up that took no more then five minutes.  So plan for a LOT of wasted time comming here. Everytging else was fine enough.< /Review>

üáÆüá© INDONESIA
Excerpt from Eat the World Los Angeles:
In better days you will see the the chef, or possibly another employee sitting at a nearby table cutting vegetables in preparation for the night's meals. For now, the very brief takeout interactions with the friendly pair will have to do. They do pride themselves in the family-run aspect of their business and even go to pains on their website and in person to project "not a fast-paced setting.

This of course can be a welcome relief if you let it be, and future meals here are looked forward to with groups of friends and plenty of time.</Review>

< name>
Kevin Kou< /name>
<date>1607921027403< /date><Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
People talk about Borneo Kalimantan vs Simpang Asia as the places to go for authentic Indonesian food, but this place is every bit as good as those two, and in some dishes, Wong surpasses them.

I had the nasi goreng w/ shrimp (amazing that shrimp is only +$1 on top of the default chicken/beef) along with ayam penyet and they were both delicious. Portion sizes were A+. If I had known those two dishes were so good I probably would've gotten the belacan kangkung just to round out the meal.

I honestly felt bad I didn't buy more food during my takeout cause it's niche restaurants like this that are hurting the most during lockdown. I hope this place survives!< /Review>

<review>The food wasn't bad but I've had better Indonesian food. The food mostly had a sweet taste to it which I guess is part of the cuisine of this part of Indonesia. The issue I have however is the price. The portions are not worth the prices and we had a party of 5 with 2 kids and 3 adults. We ordered one large bowl of rice and got charged $12. This is the most I've ever paid for a bowl of plain white rice at any Asian restaurant. A chicken entree was $17, it said whole chicken, so I assumed a large portion. What came out was Cornish hen, the size of 2 legs of regular chicken. $11 for 5 small skewers of chicken satay is pricey, and unfortunately the meat seemed weird. Sort of makes you stop and wonder if it's actually chicken.

For 3 adults and 2 young kids we paid around $87, which is over $20/person. I'm not sure how that happened, but needless to say, that's the last time I go here.<//review>< user>

< Rate>
4</Rate>
< text>
Slowest restaurant in SGV:

So this is was originally gonna be a one star review. I hadn't planned on coming but end up here, walked in and ordered 2 dishes - a pressed chicken and an ox tail soup. 20 minutes later and nothing happened. a little hungry I waited for another 5 min and had to ask the waiter/owner what the deal is. He got into this somewhat defensive rant about how this isn't a McDonald nor a Panda Express and his stuff are all cooked slowly, implied that I only know fast food, and how I should've checked out their social media to find out their minimum wait is 30-40 minutes.

Taken aback a little by his attitude, and somewhat offended that I am expected to read up social media before heading into a place, I started this review fully intending on giving it a 1 star. But then the food arrived. It's 34 minute wait, but it was delicious. The chicken was very tender and full of flavor. The soup was well cooked and really nothing to complain about.

So in the end, based on their food quality this place deserves a 5 star. But I need to dock at least a star for the slowness and rudeness. Yes your restaurant make everything slow and it tastes great, but there's no reason to assume everyone know about your process - a simple "Is this the first time you've been with us?" and "we cook everything halal and the wait time is a little long" BEFORE I ordered food could've smoothed things out considerably. Better yet, put that on your door.

In short, this place tastes great, but is SUPER slow. Best option is to look up their menu, order ahead of time and come when the dishes are ready. The owner is a bit of a condescending blow hard (could be a language thing, who knows). Come in with the right expectations and you'll have a good time.</text>

<username>Valhalla LGK20<//username><time>1514187757557< /time><Rating>5</Rating>< text>
I have visited at least 5 Indonesian restaurants in the California and Washington. This one is the best! Excellent! The cook says their food is halal which I don't really care as long as the food is good. :D

The service is a bit slow but it was worth the wait. The selection of food is ample and I believe it is more than you could make in your own kitchen; if you could cook. :P

I don't know why people grumble about the parking. They should come to enjoy the food but not the parking.

I would definitely come again and again and again....

<Resp>None<//Resp><Date>1531080906437<//Date>< Text>
In the San Gabriel Valley finding Indonesian food is hard. We used to eat at Indo Kitchen, which was a fabulous little place, but they closed shop a while back. We Googled Indonesian food in SGV and came.up with this GEM! The tiny staff is attentive and amazingly friendly. And the food? Wonderful! We had Gado Gado, Longtong, Fried Tahu and Tempeh and noodles. All so great. Home made Sambal Badjak is so hot but so flavorful. And Es Telor for dessert was what we needed on a 110 degree day in Alhambra.< /Text>

Probably one of the worst Indonesian restaurants that I've visited. The service was extremely slow...

The lamb satays I ordered were dry because they were leftovers from a previous day and reheated. The steamed  fish dumplings were cold in the centre and lukewarm from the outside because they were reheated from the microwave! The dumplings had no flavour and the texture was extremely rubbery. The Nasi Goreng was rather bland.< /text>

I scheduled an appointment with Geek Squad a week ahead of time for an iPhone X battery replacement. This was a very frustrating experience.

Not a true electronics store anymore. It's an electronic toy store. Did not meet the needs of a person needing electronic goods to fix or repair said electronic toys or goods. Staff was rude and not at all helpful. Was raining and they were out of cats. I asked if someone could get some of the carts from the parking lot, the Geek Squard girl said, and I quote, "but it's raining." Really? You don't say. Then after I asked again she said that she's send someone out to get carts "when it stopped raining." Then I discovered they no longer carried real electronic items, so I left and drove up to an amazing electronics store that not only had the cords I needed but we're helpful and kind. Skip Best Buy, as it truly isn't a Best buy, and go up the road a bit to San Mateo Electronics. Much better shop.< /review>
